// Hand-written jr-high/high-school reading passages that OVERRIDE the auto-templated
// ones (matched by slug). Structure: Hook → Context → Key Idea → Example → Legacy.
// Facts are aligned to the prose so the 3-random-question generator still works.
// Being filled in batches; anything not here yet falls back to the auto passage.
window.HIST_AUTHORED = [
  { slug:'mahatma_gandhi', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'India', birthplace:'Porbandar', spouse:'Kasturba Gandhi', work:'satyagraha', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Mahatma Gandhi was a leader from India, which was ruled by the British Empire during much of his life. He was born in Porbandar in 1869 and later studied law in London. Gandhi first used peaceful protest while living in South Africa, where he fought unfair treatment of Indian people. When he returned to India, he became one of the most important leaders in India's struggle for independence from British rule. Gandhi believed in satyagraha, which means using truth, courage, and nonviolent resistance instead of violence. One famous example was the Salt March in 1930, when he walked with followers to protest a British tax on salt. He was married to Kasturba Gandhi, and his ideas later inspired civil rights leaders around the world." },

  { slug:'nelson_mandela', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'South Africa', birthplace:'Mvezo', work:'ending apartheid', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Nelson Mandela was a leader from South Africa, a country where unfair laws called apartheid separated people by the color of their skin. He was born in the village of Mvezo in 1918 and trained as a lawyer. Mandela joined the fight against apartheid, believing that Black South Africans deserved equal rights. Because he spoke out and helped organize protests, the government sent him to prison, where he stayed for 27 years. Instead of giving up, he became a symbol of hope around the world. When he was finally freed in 1990, he chose forgiveness over revenge, and in 1994 he became South Africa's first Black president — showing that patience and courage can defeat even the most powerful injustice." },

  { slug:'martin_luther_king_jr', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'United States', birthplace:'Atlanta', spouse:'Coretta Scott King', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Martin Luther King Jr. was a leader from the United States during a time when Black Americans were treated unfairly under segregation laws. He was born in Atlanta in 1929 and became a minister like his father. King believed that people could win equal rights through peaceful protest instead of violence, an idea he learned partly from Mahatma Gandhi. In 1963 he led the March on Washington and gave his famous 'I Have a Dream' speech, calling for people of all races to be judged by their character. He was married to Coretta Scott King, who continued his work after he was killed in 1968. His courage helped end segregation and inspired movements for fairness all over the world." },

  { slug:'abraham_lincoln', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Hodgenville', spouse:'Mary Todd Lincoln', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Abraham Lincoln was the sixteenth president of the United States during the most dangerous time in the nation's history. He was born in a log cabin near Hodgenville, Kentucky, in 1809 and taught himself to read by firelight. When Lincoln became president in 1861, several Southern states left the country to protect slavery, starting the Civil War. Lincoln fought to keep the nation together and, in 1863, issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared enslaved people in the rebelling states to be free. He was married to Mary Todd Lincoln, and he guided the country until the war was nearly won. Lincoln was assassinated in 1865, but he is remembered for holding the nation together and helping to end slavery." },

  { slug:'leonardo_da_vinci', facts:{ field:'artist', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Vinci', work:'the Mona Lisa', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Leonardo da Vinci was an artist and inventor from Italy during the Renaissance, a time when Europe rediscovered art and learning. He was born near the town of Vinci in 1452 and showed his talent for drawing at an early age. Leonardo believed that art and science belonged together, so he studied the human body, water, birds, and light to make his paintings more real. He is most famous for painting the Mona Lisa, whose mysterious smile still draws crowds today. In his notebooks he sketched flying machines and other inventions hundreds of years before they were built. Leonardo's endless curiosity made him a symbol of the creative, questioning spirit of the Renaissance." },

  { slug:'isaac_newton', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'Woolsthorpe', work:'the law of gravity', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Isaac Newton was a scientist from England who changed the way people understand the universe. He was born in the village of Woolsthorpe in 1643 and grew up curious about how things move. According to a famous story, watching an apple fall led Newton to wonder about the force that pulls objects toward the Earth. He explained this force with his law of gravity and also wrote three laws of motion that describe how everything from balls to planets moves. Newton's ideas became the foundation of physics and helped later scientists send rockets into space. He is remembered as one of the greatest scientific thinkers who ever lived." },

  { slug:'charles_darwin', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'Shrewsbury', work:'the theory of evolution', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Charles Darwin was a naturalist from England who studied plants, animals, and fossils. He was born in Shrewsbury in 1809 and, as a young man, sailed around the world on a ship called HMS Beagle. On islands like the Galápagos, Darwin noticed that animals of the same kind looked slightly different from place to place. This led him to the theory of evolution by natural selection — the idea that living things slowly change over many generations to fit their surroundings. He explained his findings in a book called On the Origin of Species, which surprised and even upset many people at the time. Today his work is a cornerstone of modern biology." },

  { slug:'william_shakespeare', facts:{ field:'playwright', country:'England', birthplace:'Stratford-upon-Avon', spouse:'Anne Hathaway', work:'Hamlet', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"William Shakespeare was a playwright and poet from England, often called the greatest writer in the English language. He was born in the town of Stratford-upon-Avon in 1564 and later moved to London, where he wrote and performed plays. Shakespeare understood people deeply, and his stories explore love, jealousy, power, and revenge in ways that still feel true today. He wrote about 37 plays, including Hamlet, Romeo and Juliet, and Macbeth, and even invented hundreds of new words. He was married to Anne Hathaway and had three children back in Stratford. Four hundred years later, his plays are still performed all over the world." },

  { slug:'cleopatra', facts:{ field:'pharaoh', country:'Egypt', birthplace:'Alexandria', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Cleopatra was the last pharaoh, or ruler, of ancient Egypt. She was born in the great city of Alexandria around 69 BCE, at a time when the powerful Roman Empire was growing nearby. Cleopatra was famous for her sharp mind and her ability to speak many languages, which helped her deal with foreign leaders. To protect Egypt's independence, she formed alliances with two of Rome's most powerful men, Julius Caesar and Mark Antony. In the end, Rome grew too strong, and after her death Egypt became part of the Roman Empire. Cleopatra is still remembered as one of history's most clever and legendary rulers." },

  { slug:'julius_caesar', facts:{ field:'general', country:'Rome', birthplace:'Rome', work:'the Roman calendar', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Julius Caesar was a general and ruler of ancient Rome whose choices changed history. He was born in Rome around 100 BCE and rose to power by winning wars and gaining the loyalty of his soldiers. Caesar conquered new lands for Rome and became so powerful that he was named dictator for life. He also reformed the calendar, creating a 365-day year that is the ancestor of the one we use today. Many Roman senators feared he had too much power, and in 44 BCE they assassinated him. His death led to years of struggle that ended the Roman Republic and began the Roman Empire." },

  { slug:'napoleon', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'France', birthplace:'Ajaccio', work:'the Napoleonic Code', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Napoleon Bonaparte was a general who became the emperor of France. He was born on the island of Corsica in 1769 and rose quickly through the army during the chaos of the French Revolution. A brilliant military leader, Napoleon conquered much of Europe and spread new ideas about law and government. He created the Napoleonic Code, a set of laws that treated citizens more equally and still influences many countries today. But his endless wars cost millions of lives, and after a terrible defeat he was finally beaten at the Battle of Waterloo in 1815. Napoleon remains one of history's most studied and debated leaders, admired for his genius and blamed for his ambition." },

  { slug:'confucius', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'China', birthplace:'Qufu', work:'the Analects', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Confucius was a teacher and philosopher from ancient China whose ideas shaped an entire culture. He was born in the town of Qufu around 551 BCE, during a time of war and disorder among Chinese states. Confucius believed that society would be peaceful if people treated each other with respect, honesty, and kindness, especially within families. He traveled from place to place teaching students, and his sayings were later collected in a book called the Analects. Chinese governments used his ideas about good behavior and fair leadership for more than two thousand years. Today Confucius is still honored as one of the most important thinkers in all of history." },

  { slug:'genghis_khan', facts:{ field:'conqueror', country:'Mongolia', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Genghis Khan was a warrior and ruler from Mongolia who built the largest connected land empire the world has ever seen. He was born around 1162 and had a hard childhood, uniting the scattered Mongol tribes into one powerful nation. Genghis Khan led fierce armies of skilled horsemen who conquered lands across Asia and into Europe. His conquests were extremely violent and cost the lives of huge numbers of people. Yet his empire also connected distant cultures, protected trade along the Silk Road, and allowed people to follow different religions. Genghis Khan is remembered as both a brutal conqueror and a leader who linked the ancient world together." },

  { slug:'christopher_columbus', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Genoa', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Christopher Columbus was an explorer, born in the Italian city of Genoa around 1451, who sailed for the kingdom of Spain. Most Europeans of his time did not know that two huge continents lay across the Atlantic Ocean. In 1492 Columbus led three ships west, hoping to reach Asia, and instead landed on islands in the Americas. His voyages opened lasting contact between Europe and the Americas, changing both worlds forever. But his arrival also brought terrible harm — disease, slavery, and violence — to the Indigenous peoples who already lived there. Columbus is remembered today as a bold sailor whose journeys had enormous and often tragic consequences." },

  { slug:'vincent_van_gogh', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Netherlands', birthplace:'Zundert', work:'The Starry Night', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Vincent van Gogh was a painter from the Netherlands whose bold colors helped shape modern art. He was born in the village of Zundert in 1853 and did not begin painting seriously until he was almost thirty. Van Gogh painted with thick, swirling brushstrokes and bright colors that showed his powerful emotions. His most famous painting, The Starry Night, shows a glowing night sky above a quiet town. Sadly, he struggled with poverty and mental illness and sold almost no paintings during his life. Only after his death did the world recognize his genius, and today his works are among the most loved and valuable paintings ever made." },

  { slug:'pablo_picasso', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Spain', birthplace:'Málaga', work:'Cubism', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Pablo Picasso was an artist from Spain who changed the rules of modern art. He was born in the city of Málaga in 1881 and could draw beautifully even as a child. As an adult, Picasso decided that art did not have to copy the real world exactly. With a friend, he helped invent a style called Cubism, which breaks objects into flat shapes seen from many angles at once. He also painted Guernica, a huge black-and-white picture that protests the horrors of war. Over his long life Picasso created tens of thousands of works and became one of the most famous and influential artists of all time." },

  { slug:'ludwig_van_beethoven', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Bonn', work:'the Ninth Symphony', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Ludwig van Beethoven was a composer from Germany whose music helped begin a bold new age of classical music. He was born in the city of Bonn in 1770 and became a brilliant pianist as a young man. Beethoven wrote powerful symphonies, sonatas, and concertos full of strong emotion and surprise. Astonishingly, he slowly lost his hearing, yet he kept composing — even writing his famous Ninth Symphony after he had become almost completely deaf. That symphony's 'Ode to Joy' celebrates friendship and hope among all people. Beethoven proved that great art can rise out of great struggle, and his music is still performed around the world today." },

  { slug:'rosa_parks', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Tuskegee', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Rosa Parks was a civil rights activist from the United States who helped change unfair laws with a single brave choice. She was born in Tuskegee, Alabama, in 1913, at a time when segregation forced Black Americans to use separate seats, schools, and services. In 1955, Parks refused to give up her bus seat to a white passenger in Montgomery, and she was arrested. Her stand sparked the Montgomery Bus Boycott, in which Black residents refused to ride the buses for over a year. The boycott helped launch the modern civil rights movement and made Rosa Parks a lasting symbol of quiet courage. Her example showed that ordinary people can help change history by standing up for what is right." },

  { slug:'frederick_douglass', facts:{ field:'abolitionist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Talbot County', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Frederick Douglass was a writer and speaker from the United States who fought to end slavery. He was born enslaved in Talbot County, Maryland, around 1818, and secretly taught himself to read even though it was against the law. As a young man, Douglass escaped to freedom in the North, where he began giving powerful speeches about the cruelty of slavery. He wrote books about his own life that convinced many people that slavery must end. During the Civil War, he urged President Lincoln to let Black men fight for the Union and for their own freedom. Frederick Douglass showed how education and courage could turn a person born into slavery into one of the greatest leaders in American history." },

  { slug:'harriet_tubman', facts:{ field:'abolitionist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Dorchester County', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Harriet Tubman was a hero of the fight against slavery in the United States. She was born enslaved in Dorchester County, Maryland, around 1822, and suffered greatly as a child. As a young woman, Tubman escaped to freedom in the North, but she did not stop there. She returned to the South again and again, secretly guiding many enslaved people to freedom along a network of safe houses called the Underground Railroad. During the Civil War she even served the Union army as a scout, nurse, and spy. Known for her bravery and cleverness, Harriet Tubman risked her life over and over so that others could be free." },

  { slug:'socrates', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Greece', birthplace:'Athens', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Socrates was a philosopher from the ancient Greek city of Athens, a place famous for its early experiments with democracy. He was born around 470 BCE and, unlike most famous thinkers, never wrote down his ideas. Instead, Socrates walked through the city asking people careful questions about big topics like justice, courage, and truth. This questioning method, now called the Socratic method, showed people how little they truly understood and pushed them to think for themselves. His challenges annoyed powerful men, and he was put on trial and sentenced to death. Yet his student Plato wrote down his conversations, and Socrates is still honored as a father of Western philosophy." },

  { slug:'plato', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Greece', birthplace:'Athens', work:'The Republic', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Plato was a philosopher from ancient Athens and one of the most important thinkers in history. He was born around 428 BCE and studied under the great questioner Socrates. After Socrates was put to death, Plato wrote down many of their conversations as 'dialogues' so their ideas would not be lost. In his book The Republic, Plato imagined what a perfectly just society and a wise leader might look like. He also founded a school called the Academy, one of the first universities in the Western world. Plato's ideas about truth, justice, and government have been studied for more than two thousand years." },

  { slug:'aristotle', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Greece', birthplace:'Stagira', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Aristotle was a philosopher and scientist from ancient Greece who tried to understand almost everything. He was born in the town of Stagira around 384 BCE and studied at Plato's Academy in Athens. Aristotle believed that people should learn by observing the real world, so he studied animals, weather, government, and the stars. He created systems for organizing knowledge, including the rules of logic that we still use to reason carefully. He even became the personal teacher of a young prince named Alexander, who would grow up to conquer much of the known world. For centuries afterward, scholars in Europe and the Middle East called Aristotle simply 'the Philosopher.'" },

  { slug:'archimedes', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'Greece', birthplace:'Syracuse', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Archimedes was a mathematician and inventor from the ancient Greek city of Syracuse. He was born around 287 BCE and became famous for using math to explain how the physical world works. Archimedes studied levers and pulleys and reportedly said that, given a place to stand, he could move the whole Earth. According to legend, he discovered how to measure the volume of objects while taking a bath and shouted 'Eureka!' — meaning 'I found it!' He also designed clever machines to defend his city from Roman attack. His discoveries in geometry and engineering influenced science for nearly two thousand years." },

  { slug:'michelangelo', facts:{ field:'sculptor', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Caprese', work:'the statue of David', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Michelangelo was an artist from Italy and one of the greatest talents of the Renaissance. He was born in the village of Caprese in 1475 and showed astonishing skill as both a sculptor and a painter. From a single block of marble he carved the statue of David, a giant figure so lifelike that people could hardly believe it was stone. He also spent four years lying on his back to paint the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel in Rome, filling it with hundreds of figures. Michelangelo worked with fierce energy well into old age, always chasing perfection. His art still amazes millions of visitors every year." },

  { slug:'wolfgang_amadeus_mozart', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Austria', birthplace:'Salzburg', spouse:'Constanze Mozart', work:'The Magic Flute', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart was a composer from Austria and one of the greatest musical geniuses who ever lived. He was born in the city of Salzburg in 1756 and was a child prodigy, playing the piano and composing music before he was six years old. As a boy, he toured Europe performing for kings and queens. Mozart wrote more than 600 pieces of music, including symphonies, concertos, and operas such as The Magic Flute. He was married to Constanze Mozart, but he struggled with money and died young, at just 35. Even so, his beautiful, joyful music is still loved and performed all over the world." },

  { slug:'johann_sebastian_bach', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Eisenach', spouse:'Anna Magdalena Bach', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Johann Sebastian Bach was a composer and organist from Germany, considered one of the greatest musicians in history. He was born in the town of Eisenach in 1685 into a large family of musicians. Bach spent his life working for churches and courts, writing music for choirs, organs, and small orchestras. He was a master of counterpoint, weaving several melodies together so they fit like the gears of a clock. He was married to Anna Magdalena Bach, and several of his many children became composers too. Though he was not world-famous in his own time, Bach's music is now studied by nearly every serious musician." },

  { slug:'george_washington', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Virginia', spouse:'Martha Washington', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"George Washington was a general and the first president of the United States. He was born in the colony of Virginia in 1732, when America was still ruled by Britain. When the thirteen colonies rebelled, Washington was chosen to lead the ragged American army through the long and difficult Revolutionary War. His steady leadership helped the colonies win their independence. Afterward, he could have made himself a king, but instead he helped create a republic and served two terms as president before stepping down. He was married to Martha Washington, and he is often called the 'Father of His Country.'" },

  { slug:'benjamin_franklin', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'United States', birthplace:'Boston', work:'the lightning rod', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Benjamin Franklin was an inventor, writer, and statesman from the United States, famous for his endless curiosity. He was born in Boston in 1706 and became a successful printer before turning to science. In a famous experiment, Franklin flew a kite in a thunderstorm to study electricity, which led him to invent the lightning rod to protect buildings. He also invented bifocal glasses and a clever heating stove, and he never patented his ideas so everyone could use them. As a leader, he helped write the Declaration of Independence and won France's help during the American Revolution. Franklin showed how one curious mind could improve both science and society." },

  { slug:'thomas_jefferson', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Shadwell', work:'the Declaration of Independence', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Thomas Jefferson was a writer and the third president of the United States. He was born in Shadwell, Virginia, in 1743 and grew up loving books, science, and ideas. In 1776, Jefferson wrote most of the Declaration of Independence, including the famous words that 'all men are created equal.' As president, he doubled the size of the country by buying a huge region of land in the Louisiana Purchase. Yet Jefferson also enslaved many people, a painful contradiction with his own words about freedom. He is remembered as a brilliant thinker whose ideals shaped America even as his own life showed the nation's deep flaws." },

  { slug:'winston_churchill', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'England', work:'his wartime speeches', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Winston Churchill was the prime minister who led Britain through the darkest days of World War II. He was born in England in 1874 into a famous family and worked as a soldier and writer before entering politics. When Nazi Germany conquered much of Europe and bombed British cities, Churchill refused to surrender. His powerful wartime speeches, promising 'we shall never surrender,' helped keep his country's spirit alive. Working with the United States and the Soviet Union, Britain helped defeat Nazi Germany in 1945. Churchill's career included serious mistakes, but he is remembered above all for his courage and words during a time of great danger." },

  { slug:'franklin_d_roosevelt', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Hyde Park', spouse:'Eleanor Roosevelt', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Franklin D. Roosevelt, often called FDR, was the president who guided the United States through two enormous crises. He was born in Hyde Park, New York, in 1882 and, as an adult, was partly paralyzed by polio, yet he never stopped leading. When he became president in 1933, the country was trapped in the Great Depression, with millions out of work. Roosevelt created programs called the New Deal to give people jobs, food, and hope. Later he led the nation through most of World War II. He was married to Eleanor Roosevelt, a champion of human rights, and FDR is the only president ever elected four times." },

  { slug:'john_f_kennedy', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'Brookline', spouse:'Jacqueline Kennedy', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"John F. Kennedy was the 35th president of the United States, serving during the tense years of the Cold War. He was born in Brookline, Massachusetts, in 1917 and became one of the youngest people ever elected president. Kennedy inspired the nation with his call to public service, asking Americans what they could do for their country. He faced a frightening standoff with the Soviet Union over missiles in Cuba and helped avoid a nuclear war. He also challenged the country to land a person on the Moon before the decade ended. He was married to Jacqueline Kennedy, and his life was cut short when he was assassinated in 1963." },

  { slug:'alexander_the_great', facts:{ field:'conqueror', country:'Macedonia', birthplace:'Pella', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Alexander the Great was a young king and conqueror from the ancient kingdom of Macedonia, in northern Greece. He was born in the city of Pella in 356 BCE and was taught by the philosopher Aristotle. Becoming king at just 20, Alexander led his army on an astonishing campaign, conquering the mighty Persian Empire and marching all the way to India. By the time he died at only 32, he ruled one of the largest empires the world had ever seen. Wherever he went, he spread Greek language, art, and ideas, blending them with the cultures he conquered. His empire soon broke apart, but his legend as a brilliant general has lasted for over two thousand years." },

  { slug:'joan_of_arc', facts:{ field:'soldier', country:'France', birthplace:'Domrémy', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Joan of Arc was a peasant girl who became a military hero of France during the Middle Ages. She was born in the village of Domrémy around 1412, while France was losing a long war against England. As a teenager, Joan believed that God was calling her to save her country, and she convinced the French leaders to let her join the army. Wearing armor, she inspired the soldiers and helped win important battles, turning the tide of the war. Captured by her enemies, she was put on trial and executed when she was only about 19. Centuries later she was made a saint, and today she is a national symbol of courage and faith." },

  { slug:'marco_polo', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Venice', work:'his book of travels', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Marco Polo was an explorer from the Italian city of Venice who traveled farther than almost any European of his time. He was born around 1254 and, as a teenager, set out with his father and uncle on a journey along the Silk Road to China. There he spent many years in the service of the powerful Mongol ruler Kublai Khan. When Marco Polo finally returned home, he described the riches and wonders of Asia in a famous book of travels. Many Europeans could hardly believe his stories of paper money, huge cities, and strange customs. His book made Europeans curious about the wider world and helped inspire later explorers." },

  { slug:'amelia_earhart', facts:{ field:'aviator', country:'United States', birthplace:'Atchison', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Amelia Earhart was a pilot from the United States who became one of the most famous women in aviation history. She was born in Atchison, Kansas, in 1897, when flying was brand new and considered too dangerous for women. Earhart fell in love with airplanes and set record after record, becoming the first woman to fly alone across the Atlantic Ocean. She used her fame to encourage women to chase careers once thought impossible for them. In 1937, while trying to fly all the way around the world, her plane vanished over the Pacific Ocean and was never found. Her courage and mysterious disappearance have made her a lasting legend." },

  { slug:'neil_armstrong', facts:{ field:'astronaut', country:'United States', birthplace:'Wapakoneta', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Neil Armstrong was an American astronaut who became the first human being to walk on the Moon. He was born in Wapakoneta, Ohio, in 1930 and grew up fascinated by flight, becoming a test pilot and then an astronaut. During the Cold War, the United States and the Soviet Union were racing to reach the Moon first. In July 1969, Armstrong and his crew flew the Apollo 11 mission, and he stepped onto the Moon's surface with the words, 'That's one small step for man, one giant leap for mankind.' Millions of people around the world watched the landing on television. His calm courage made him a symbol of what humans can achieve when they dream big." },

  { slug:'charles_dickens', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', birthplace:'Portsmouth', spouse:'Catherine Dickens', work:'A Christmas Carol', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Charles Dickens was one of the most beloved writers in the history of England. He was born in Portsmouth in 1812, and as a boy his family fell into debt, forcing him to leave school and work in a factory. These hard experiences taught Dickens to care deeply about poor and struggling people. He turned his observations into famous novels such as Oliver Twist and A Christmas Carol, whose characters felt so real that readers loved and hated them. He was married to Catherine Dickens and had ten children. Through his stories, Dickens made his readers laugh, cry, and think about how society treated its poorest members." },

  { slug:'anne_frank', title:'Anne Frank', emoji:'✍️', img:'anne_frank.jpg', region:'W', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Frankfurt', work:'her diary', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Anne Frank was a Jewish girl whose diary became one of the most important books to come out of World War II. She was born in Frankfurt, Germany, in 1929, but her family fled to the Netherlands to escape the Nazis, who persecuted Jewish people. When the danger grew, the Franks hid in a secret set of rooms behind Anne's father's office in Amsterdam. For two years, Anne kept a diary about her fears, hopes, and dreams while in hiding. She wrote that despite everything, she still believed people were truly good at heart. After she died in a concentration camp, her diary was published, giving the world an unforgettable window into history through a young girl's eyes." },

  { slug:'hokusai', facts:{ field:'artist', country:'Japan', birthplace:'Edo', work:'The Great Wave', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Hokusai was a Japanese artist famous for his beautiful and dramatic woodblock prints. He was born in the city of Edo, now called Tokyo, in 1760, during a peaceful period in Japan's history. Hokusai created his most famous image, The Great Wave off Kanagawa, which shows a towering blue wave curling over tiny boats with Mount Fuji in the distance. He made tens of thousands of artworks and never stopped trying to improve, saying he only began to truly understand nature in his seventies. When his prints reached Europe, they amazed painters and influenced modern art. Today The Great Wave is one of the most recognized images in the world." },

  { slug:'frida_kahlo', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Mexico', birthplace:'Coyoacán', spouse:'Diego Rivera', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Frida Kahlo was a painter from Mexico known for her bold, colorful, and deeply personal art. She was born in Coyoacán, near Mexico City, in 1907, and a terrible bus accident as a teenager left her in pain for the rest of her life. While recovering, Kahlo began to paint, especially self-portraits that showed both her suffering and her strength. Her paintings were filled with Mexican colors, symbols, and traditions, and she wore proud, traditional clothing. She was married to the famous muralist Diego Rivera, and their stormy relationship shaped much of her work. Today Frida Kahlo is celebrated around the world as a symbol of courage and Mexican culture." },

  { slug:'sun_tzu', facts:{ field:'general', country:'China', work:'The Art of War', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Sun Tzu was an ancient Chinese general and thinker, traditionally believed to have written a famous book called The Art of War. He is said to have lived around 500 BCE, during a time when Chinese states often fought one another. The Art of War teaches that the smartest leaders win by careful planning, discipline, and understanding both themselves and their opponents. Sun Tzu argued that the greatest victory is to win without even having to fight. His ideas about strategy have been studied for more than two thousand years, not just by soldiers but also by business leaders and coaches. Few short books have had such a long and wide influence." },

  { slug:'sacagawea', facts:{ field:'guide', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Sacagawea was a young Shoshone woman who played a vital role in exploring the American West. She was born around 1788 and, as a teenager, joined the famous Lewis and Clark expedition in 1805. The explorers were mapping a huge stretch of North America that was unknown to them, and Sacagawea guided them and translated with Native American nations along the way. She traveled thousands of difficult miles while carrying her baby son on her back. Her presence also signaled to other tribes that the group came in peace. Sacagawea is remembered as a symbol of the important, often overlooked roles Native Americans played in the nation's history." },

  { slug:'rumi', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'Persia', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Rumi was a Persian poet and spiritual teacher whose words are still read by millions of people today. He was born in the early 1200s in a region of Central Asia and later settled in what is now Turkey. Rumi was a respected scholar until he met a wandering mystic who changed his life and filled him with a deep love of God and of all people. From then on, Rumi poured his feelings into thousands of poems about love, kindness, and the search for meaning. His most famous work is a long poem called the Masnavi. Centuries later, Rumi's gentle, hopeful poetry has made him one of the best-selling poets in the world." },

  { slug:'laozi', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'China', work:'the Dao De Jing', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Laozi, whose name means 'Old Master,' was an ancient Chinese thinker traditionally seen as the founder of Daoism. Little is known for certain about his life, and some scholars wonder whether he was one person or several. He is said to have lived around the 6th century BCE and to have written a short, poetic book called the Dao De Jing. Its verses teach people to live in harmony with nature, to stay humble, and to avoid forcing things. Laozi believed that the wisest leaders rule gently and quietly, letting people live in peace. His ideas shaped Chinese philosophy, religion, art, and government for thousands of years." },

  { slug:'qin_shi_huang', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'China', work:'the Terracotta Army', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Qin Shi Huang was the first emperor to unite all of China under a single ruler. He was born around 259 BCE and, through fierce warfare, conquered rival kingdoms to form one empire. To hold his huge realm together, he standardized China's writing, money, and measurements, and began connecting walls into an early version of the Great Wall. But Qin Shi Huang ruled harshly, punishing those who disagreed and forcing many people to labor on his projects. Obsessed with living forever, he had a vast underground tomb built, guarded by the Terracotta Army — thousands of life-sized clay soldiers. His empire fell soon after his death, yet he had shaped the idea of a united China that still lasts today." },

  { slug:'nefertiti', facts:{ field:'queen', country:'Egypt', spouse:'Akhenaten', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Nefertiti was a powerful queen of ancient Egypt, remembered for her beauty and her influence. She lived in the 1300s BCE and was married to the pharaoh Akhenaten. Together they made a bold and unusual change, leading Egypt to worship a single sun god instead of its many traditional gods. Nefertiti appears in ancient artwork standing beside her husband as an equal, which was rare for a queen. A famous painted statue of her head, discovered by archaeologists, has made her one of the most recognized faces from the ancient world. Much about her life remains a mystery, which only adds to her fame." },

  { slug:'louis_pasteur', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'France', birthplace:'Dole', work:'pasteurization', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Louis Pasteur was a scientist from France whose discoveries saved countless lives. He was born in the town of Dole in 1822 and became curious about the tiny living things called microbes, or germs. Pasteur proved that germs, not bad air, cause many diseases and cause food to spoil. He invented a process now called pasteurization, which gently heats milk and other liquids to kill harmful germs and keep them safe to drink. He also developed vaccines that protected people and animals from deadly illnesses like rabies. Pasteur's work created the science of microbiology and changed medicine, food safety, and public health forever." },

  { slug:'alexander_fleming', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Scotland', work:'penicillin', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Alexander Fleming was a scientist from Scotland who made one of the most important discoveries in medicine — almost by accident. He was born in 1881 and worked as a doctor studying bacteria, the germs that cause many infections. In 1928, Fleming returned from vacation to find that a mold had grown on one of his dishes and killed the bacteria around it. He realized the mold produced a germ-fighting substance, which he named penicillin. Penicillin became the first true antibiotic, a medicine that cures infections that once killed people. Fleming's lucky discovery, carefully studied, has saved millions of lives around the world." },

  { slug:'michael_faraday', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'London', work:'the electric motor', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Michael Faraday was a scientist from England who helped unlock the secrets of electricity. He was born in London in 1791 into a poor family and had very little schooling. Working first as a bookbinder, Faraday read the science books he was binding and taught himself. He went on to discover that a moving magnet can create an electric current, a principle that led him to build the first electric motor and generator. These inventions made it possible to produce and use electricity on a large scale. Though he never had a fancy education, Faraday became one of the greatest experimental scientists in history." },

  { slug:'nicolaus_copernicus', facts:{ field:'astronomer', country:'Poland', birthplace:'Toruń', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Nicolaus Copernicus was an astronomer from Poland who dared to rethink the entire universe. He was born in the city of Toruń in 1473, at a time when nearly everyone believed the Earth stood still at the center of everything. After years of careful study, Copernicus concluded that the Earth and the other planets actually orbit the Sun. This idea was so shocking that he waited until the end of his life to publish it. His book quietly began a scientific revolution that would later be proven by astronomers like Galileo and Kepler. Copernicus showed that even the oldest, most trusted beliefs should be tested against careful observation." },

  { slug:'johannes_kepler', facts:{ field:'astronomer', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Weil der Stadt', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Johannes Kepler was an astronomer and mathematician from Germany who discovered how the planets move. He was born in the town of Weil der Stadt in 1571 and had poor eyesight, yet he loved studying the sky. Using years of careful measurements, Kepler figured out that planets travel around the Sun in stretched circles called ellipses, not perfect circles as people had believed. He described this and other patterns in three famous laws of planetary motion. His discoveries helped prove that the Earth orbits the Sun and later helped Isaac Newton explain gravity. Kepler showed the power of combining careful math with patient observation." },

  { slug:'stephen_hawking', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'Oxford', work:'A Brief History of Time', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Stephen Hawking was a physicist from England who explored the biggest mysteries of the universe. He was born in Oxford in 1942 and became fascinated by space, time, and black holes. As a young man, Hawking was diagnosed with a disease called ALS that slowly paralyzed his body, yet his mind stayed sharp and he kept working for decades. Using a computer and a voice machine to communicate, he made major discoveries about black holes and the beginning of the universe. His book A Brief History of Time explained these giant ideas to ordinary readers and became a worldwide bestseller. Hawking showed that curiosity and determination can overcome even the hardest challenges." },

  { slug:'jane_goodall', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'England', birthplace:'London', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Jane Goodall is a scientist from England famous for her study of wild chimpanzees. She was born in London in 1934 and loved animals from the time she was a child. In 1960 she traveled to a forest in Tanzania, in Africa, to observe chimpanzees up close, something few scientists had done. Goodall discovered that chimpanzees make and use tools and have close family bonds, which changed how people understand animals. Later she became a global leader in protecting wildlife and the environment, encouraging young people to take action. Her patient work in the forest turned her into one of the most respected scientists in the world." },

  { slug:'ferdinand_magellan', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'Portugal', work:'the first voyage around the world', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Ferdinand Magellan was an explorer from Portugal who led the first expedition to sail all the way around the world. He was born around 1480 and sailed for Spain, hoping to reach the rich Spice Islands by traveling west. In 1519 he set out with five ships across the Atlantic and found a passage at the tip of South America into a huge, calm ocean he named the Pacific. The voyage was long and brutal, and Magellan himself was killed in a battle in the Philippines before it ended. But one of his ships completed the journey, proving for the first time that the world could be circled by sea. His voyage forever changed how people understood the size and shape of the Earth." },

  { slug:'james_cook', facts:{ field:'explorer', country:'England', birthplace:'Marton', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"James Cook was an explorer and mapmaker from England who charted large parts of the Pacific Ocean. He was born in the village of Marton in 1728 and rose from humble beginnings to become a skilled ship captain. On three long voyages, Cook mapped the coasts of New Zealand and eastern Australia and reached many Pacific islands with great accuracy. He was one of the first captains to keep his sailors healthy on long voyages by improving their diet. His journeys brought European contact to many Pacific peoples, which had lasting and sometimes harmful effects on them. Cook is remembered as a brilliant navigator whose maps guided sailors for generations." },

  { slug:'queen_victoria', facts:{ field:'queen', country:'England', birthplace:'London', spouse:'Prince Albert', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Queen Victoria ruled the United Kingdom for more than 60 years, one of the longest reigns in British history. She was born in London in 1819 and became queen at just 18 years old. During her reign, called the Victorian era, Britain grew into a huge empire and led the world in industry, trade, and invention. Victoria was married to Prince Albert, and after he died she wore black mourning clothes for the rest of her life. Her name came to stand for a whole age of factories, railways, and strict manners. When she died in 1901, she had ruled over a quarter of the world's people." },

  { slug:'catherine_the_great', facts:{ field:'empress', country:'Russia', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Catherine the Great was an empress who ruled Russia for over 30 years and made it a major European power. She was born a German princess in 1729 and married into the Russian royal family. When her husband proved to be a weak and unpopular ruler, Catherine seized the throne for herself. As empress, she expanded Russia's borders, built schools and hospitals, and welcomed the new ideas of the Enlightenment. She loved art and collected paintings that became one of the world's greatest museums. Yet her glittering reign was also built on the harsh system of serfdom, which kept most Russians poor and unfree." },

  { slug:'charlemagne', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'France', era:'over a thousand years ago' },
    text:"Charlemagne, whose name means 'Charles the Great,' was a king who united much of western Europe during the Middle Ages. He was born around 748 and became king of the Franks, a people living in what is now France and Germany. Through many wars, Charlemagne built a large empire and, in the year 800, was crowned emperor by the pope. He encouraged learning, ordered the building of schools, and helped preserve ancient books during a time of disorder. His empire did not last long after his death, but it planted the seeds of later European nations. Charlemagne is often called the 'Father of Europe.'" },

  { slug:'theodore_roosevelt', facts:{ field:'president', country:'United States', birthplace:'New York City', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Theodore Roosevelt was the energetic 26th president of the United States. He was born in New York City in 1858 and was a sickly child who built up his strength through exercise and adventure. As president in the early 1900s, Roosevelt fought against powerful companies that treated workers and customers unfairly. He loved the outdoors and protected millions of acres of forests, creating many national parks and monuments. He also helped the United States become a stronger power on the world stage. Bold and larger-than-life, Roosevelt showed how a president could use the office to push for big changes." },

  { slug:'simo_n_boli_var', facts:{ field:'general', country:'Venezuela', birthplace:'Caracas', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Simón Bolívar was a general and leader who helped free much of South America from Spanish rule. He was born into a wealthy family in Caracas, Venezuela, in 1783, when Spain controlled most of the continent. Inspired by ideas of liberty, Bolívar led armies across mountains and jungles in a long fight for independence. His victories helped create several new nations, including Venezuela, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Bolivia, which was named in his honor. He dreamed of uniting these countries into one strong republic, but they soon split apart. Known as 'El Libertador' — the Liberator — Bolívar remains a hero across Latin America." },

  { slug:'jane_austen', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', birthplace:'Steventon', work:'Pride and Prejudice', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Jane Austen was an English writer whose novels are still loved more than 200 years after she wrote them. She was born in the village of Steventon in 1775, the daughter of a country clergyman. Austen wrote sharp, funny stories about young women, families, money, and marriage in the England of her time. Her most famous novel, Pride and Prejudice, follows the clever Elizabeth Bennet as she navigates love and society. Austen published her books without her name on them, and few people knew who the author was during her life. Today she is celebrated as one of the greatest and wittiest novelists in the English language." },

  { slug:'leo_tolstoy', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Russia', spouse:'Sophia Tolstaya', work:'War and Peace', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Leo Tolstoy was a Russian writer often ranked among the greatest novelists of all time. He was born in 1828 on his family's country estate and grew up as a wealthy nobleman. Tolstoy wrote enormous, detailed novels that explored love, war, family, and the meaning of life. His masterpiece War and Peace follows many characters through Russia's struggle against Napoleon's invasion. He was married to Sophia Tolstaya, who helped copy his huge manuscripts by hand. Later in life Tolstoy gave up his riches and preached simple living and nonviolence, ideas that influenced leaders like Mahatma Gandhi." },

  { slug:'homer', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'Greece', work:'the Odyssey', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Homer is the ancient Greek poet believed to have created two of the most famous stories in Western literature. He is thought to have lived around the 8th century BCE, though so little is known about him that some wonder if he was a single person at all. Homer is credited with the Iliad, about the great Trojan War, and the Odyssey, about the hero Odysseus and his long, adventurous journey home. These epic poems were first performed out loud, passed down by memory before they were written. They are filled with gods, monsters, heroes, and lessons about courage and cleverness. For nearly three thousand years, Homer's stories have inspired writers, artists, and readers." },

  { slug:'maya_angelou', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'United States', birthplace:'St. Louis', work:'I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Maya Angelou was an American poet, writer, and civil rights activist. She was born in St. Louis in 1928 and endured a difficult and painful childhood in the segregated South. As an adult, Angelou worked as a dancer, singer, and actress before becoming a writer. Her book I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings tells the true story of her early life and became one of the most important works in American literature. She wrote with honesty about racism, hardship, and hope, and read a poem at a president's inauguration. Angelou's warm, powerful words continue to inspire people to face pain with dignity and courage." },

  { slug:'claude_monet', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'France', birthplace:'Paris', work:'Impressionism', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Claude Monet was a French painter who helped start a whole new style of art called Impressionism. He was born in Paris in 1840 and loved painting outdoors, directly from nature. Instead of making every detail sharp and exact, Monet used quick, loose brushstrokes to capture the changing light and color of a moment. One of his paintings, titled Impression, Sunrise, gave the Impressionist movement its name. He often painted the same scene — like his garden's water lilies — many times to show how it looked at different times of day. Monet's fresh, colorful way of seeing the world changed the course of modern art." },

  { slug:'mao_zedong', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'China', birthplace:'Shaoshan', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Mao Zedong was the leader who founded the People's Republic of China in 1949. He was born in the village of Shaoshan in 1893 and became a leader of the Chinese Communist Party. After a long civil war, Mao and his followers took control of China and reshaped the country according to communist ideas. He aimed to end old inequalities, but his programs, such as the Great Leap Forward and the Cultural Revolution, led to famine, chaos, and the deaths of millions of people. Mao remains a hugely important and deeply controversial figure. His decisions transformed China and still shape the country today." },

  { slug:'ashoka', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'India', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Ashoka was an emperor of ancient India who ruled one of the largest empires in the region's history. He was born around 304 BCE and, early in his reign, expanded his empire through brutal warfare. After a terrible battle that killed and displaced huge numbers of people, Ashoka was filled with regret and changed his ways completely. He embraced Buddhism and its message of peace, kindness, and respect for all living things. Ashoka had his new ideals carved onto stone pillars across his empire and built hospitals and roads for his people. He is remembered as a conqueror who chose compassion over cruelty." },

  { slug:'gautama_buddha', facts:{ field:'teacher', country:'India', birthplace:'Lumbini', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Gautama Buddha was a spiritual teacher whose ideas grew into the religion of Buddhism. He was born a prince named Siddhartha around the 5th century BCE, in Lumbini, in what is now Nepal. Living in a palace, he was shielded from suffering, but when he finally saw sickness, old age, and death, he left his comfortable life to search for answers. After years of meditation, he reached a deep understanding, or 'enlightenment,' and became known as the Buddha, meaning 'the Awakened One.' He taught that people can find peace by letting go of greed and treating others with compassion. His teachings spread across Asia and are followed by millions of people today." },

  { slug:'saladin', facts:{ field:'sultan', country:'Egypt', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Saladin was a Muslim sultan and general who became a legendary leader during the time of the Crusades. He was born around 1137 and rose to rule Egypt and Syria, uniting many Muslim lands. During the Crusades, European Christian armies fought to control the holy city of Jerusalem. In 1187 Saladin recaptured Jerusalem, and unlike many conquerors of his time, he treated the defeated people with unusual mercy. Even his enemies, including the English king Richard the Lionheart, respected his honor and generosity. Saladin is remembered across the world as a symbol of courage, wisdom, and fairness." },

  { slug:'cyrus_the_great', facts:{ field:'king', country:'Persia', work:'the Persian Empire', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Cyrus the Great was the king who founded the mighty Persian Empire in the 6th century BCE. He was born in the region of Persia, in what is now Iran, and through skillful leadership conquered many neighboring lands. At its height, his empire stretched across much of the ancient Middle East, making it the largest the world had yet seen. What set Cyrus apart was how he ruled: he allowed conquered peoples to keep their own religions and customs. He famously freed the Jewish people from captivity and let them return home. For his fairness, Cyrus is remembered as one of the wisest rulers of the ancient world." },

  { slug:'ramesses_ii', facts:{ field:'pharaoh', country:'Egypt', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Ramesses II, often called Ramesses the Great, was one of the most powerful pharaohs of ancient Egypt. He ruled for an astonishing 66 years during the 1200s BCE. Ramesses led his armies in famous battles and signed one of the earliest known peace treaties in history. He was also a great builder, covering Egypt with temples, statues, and monuments carved with his name. His huge temple at Abu Simbel, guarded by four giant statues of himself, still amazes visitors today. Because he ruled so long and left so many monuments, Ramesses II became a symbol of Egypt's golden age of power." },

  { slug:'tutankhamun', facts:{ field:'pharaoh', country:'Egypt', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Tutankhamun was a pharaoh of ancient Egypt who is famous today mostly because of his tomb. Often called 'King Tut,' he became pharaoh as a young boy around 1332 BCE and died when he was only about 18. During his short reign, he helped restore Egypt's old gods after his father had tried to change the religion. For thousands of years he was almost forgotten, until in 1922 archaeologists discovered his tomb still full of treasure. Inside they found golden jewelry, chariots, and his famous golden burial mask. The dazzling discovery made this once-minor king one of the most famous names from ancient Egypt." },

  { slug:'sitting_bull', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Sitting Bull was a respected leader of the Lakota Sioux people in North America. He was born around 1831, at a time when the United States was pushing Native American nations off their traditional lands. A brave warrior and a holy man, Sitting Bull refused to give up the freedom and land of his people. In 1876 he helped lead the defeat of U.S. soldiers at the Battle of the Little Bighorn. Though he was eventually forced onto a reservation, he never stopped defending his people's rights and traditions. Sitting Bull is remembered as a powerful symbol of Native American resistance and dignity." },

  { slug:'diego_rivera', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Mexico', birthplace:'Guanajuato', spouse:'Frida Kahlo', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Diego Rivera was a Mexican painter famous for his enormous wall paintings, called murals. He was born in the city of Guanajuato in 1886 and studied art in Europe before returning to Mexico. Rivera believed that art should belong to everyone, not just the rich, so he covered the walls of public buildings with huge, colorful scenes. His murals told the story of Mexico's history and celebrated its workers, farmers, and native peoples. He was married to the painter Frida Kahlo, and together they became one of the most famous couples in art. Rivera's bold public art helped shape Mexican identity and inspired mural painters around the world." },

  { slug:'louis_armstrong', facts:{ field:'musician', country:'United States', birthplace:'New Orleans', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Louis Armstrong was an American musician who helped make jazz one of the most popular kinds of music in the world. He was born in New Orleans in 1901 and grew up in great poverty, learning to play the cornet as a boy. Armstrong became a dazzling trumpet player and singer, known for his warm, gravelly voice and his joyful, inventive solos. He turned jazz into a music where a single performer could shine, changing the way musicians play. Songs like 'What a Wonderful World' made him beloved around the globe. As one of the first Black entertainers to win worldwide fame, Armstrong opened doors for many artists who followed." },

  { slug:'elvis_presley', facts:{ field:'singer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Tupelo', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Elvis Presley was an American singer often called the 'King of Rock and Roll.' He was born in Tupelo, Mississippi, in 1935 and grew up loving gospel, blues, and country music. In the 1950s, Elvis blended these styles into an exciting new sound and combined it with wild dance moves that thrilled young fans. His energetic performances and good looks made him one of the first true superstars of the television age. Songs like 'Hound Dog' and 'Jailhouse Rock' became huge hits. Elvis helped make rock and roll a worldwide sensation and remains one of the most famous entertainers in history." },

  { slug:'fre_de_ric_chopin', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Poland', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Frédéric Chopin was a composer and pianist from Poland, famous for his beautiful piano music. He was born near Warsaw in 1810 and was a child prodigy who could compose music before he was ten. As a young man he moved to Paris, France, where he became a celebrated performer and teacher. Chopin wrote almost all of his music for the piano, filling it with deep emotion, delicate melodies, and Polish folk rhythms. Though his health was fragile and he died young, his pieces are still played in concert halls everywhere. Chopin showed that the piano alone could express a whole world of feeling." },

  { slug:'pyotr_ilyich_tchaikovsky', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'Russia', birthplace:'Votkinsk', work:'The Nutcracker', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky was a composer from Russia whose dramatic, emotional music is loved around the world. He was born in the town of Votkinsk in 1840 and trained as a lawyer before deciding to devote his life to music. Tchaikovsky wrote sweeping symphonies, concertos, and operas, but he is best known for his ballets. His ballet The Nutcracker is performed every winter for holiday audiences everywhere. He filled his music with soaring melodies that could sound joyful or heartbreaking. Tchaikovsky helped Russian classical music win respect and admiration all over the world." },

  { slug:'rembrandt', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Netherlands', birthplace:'Leiden', work:'The Night Watch', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Rembrandt was a painter from the Netherlands, considered one of the greatest artists of all time. He was born in the city of Leiden in 1606, during a golden age of Dutch art and trade. Rembrandt became a master of light and shadow, making his paintings glow as if lit by real candles. His huge group portrait, The Night Watch, is one of the most famous paintings in the world. He also painted many honest self-portraits, showing his own face aging over the years. Even after fame and money slipped away later in his life, Rembrandt kept painting works that still move people today." },

  { slug:'raphael', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Urbino', work:'The School of Athens', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Raphael was an Italian painter and one of the brightest stars of the Renaissance. He was born in the town of Urbino in 1483 and showed such talent that he was famous while still young. Raphael's paintings are admired for their grace, balance, and gentle beauty. In Rome, he painted a masterpiece called The School of Athens, showing the great thinkers of ancient Greece gathered together. He worked alongside other giants of the age, including Leonardo da Vinci and Michelangelo. Raphael died at just 37, but his harmonious art influenced painters for hundreds of years." },

  { slug:'voltaire', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'France', birthplace:'Paris', work:'Candide', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Voltaire was a French writer and philosopher and one of the leading thinkers of the Enlightenment. He was born in Paris in 1694 and became famous for his sharp wit and fearless opinions. Voltaire used humor and clever stories to attack cruelty, unfairness, and the abuse of power. His short novel Candide pokes fun at people who insist that everything happens for the best. He strongly defended freedom of speech and freedom of religion, sometimes getting himself thrown in prison or exiled. Voltaire's ideas helped inspire revolutions and shaped modern ideas about liberty and tolerance." },

  { slug:'rene_descartes', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'France', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"René Descartes was a French philosopher and mathematician often called the father of modern philosophy. He was born in France in 1596 and lived during a time when science was beginning to challenge old beliefs. Descartes wanted to build knowledge on a foundation that could not be doubted. He decided that the one thing he could be sure of was that he was thinking, which led to his famous saying, 'I think, therefore I am.' In mathematics, he connected algebra and geometry, an idea still taught in schools today. Descartes taught people to question everything and to reason carefully from first principles." },

  { slug:'immanuel_kant', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Königsberg', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Immanuel Kant was a German philosopher whose ideas shaped modern thinking about knowledge and right and wrong. He was born in the city of Königsberg in 1724 and lived such a regular life that neighbors said they could set their clocks by his daily walk. Kant asked deep questions about how the human mind understands the world. He argued that people should act only in ways they would want everyone else to act, a rule about fairness and duty. His writing is famously difficult, but its influence on philosophy is enormous. Kant is remembered as one of the most important thinkers of the Enlightenment." },

  { slug:'karl_marx', facts:{ field:'philosopher', country:'Germany', birthplace:'Trier', work:'The Communist Manifesto', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Karl Marx was a German philosopher and economist whose ideas changed history. He was born in the city of Trier in 1818, during the rise of factories and the Industrial Revolution. Marx studied how societies are shaped by who owns the factories, land, and money. He argued that workers were treated unfairly by the wealthy owners and predicted that workers would one day rise up. With his friend Friedrich Engels, he wrote The Communist Manifesto, calling for a new kind of society. Marx's ideas, called communism, later inspired revolutions and governments across the world and are still debated today." },

  { slug:'adam_smith', facts:{ field:'economist', country:'Scotland', birthplace:'Kirkcaldy', work:'The Wealth of Nations', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Adam Smith was a thinker from Scotland often called the father of modern economics. He was born in the town of Kirkcaldy in 1723 and became a professor who studied how people trade, work, and grow wealthy. In his famous book The Wealth of Nations, Smith explained how, in a free market, people pursuing their own interests can end up helping society as a whole. He described this hidden force as an 'invisible hand.' His ideas encouraged free trade and shaped how governments and businesses think about money. More than 200 years later, students still study Adam Smith to understand how economies work." },

  { slug:'miguel_de_cervantes', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Spain', work:'Don Quixote', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Miguel de Cervantes was a Spanish writer who created one of the first and greatest novels in the world. He was born in Spain in 1547 and lived an adventurous, difficult life, even spending years as a captive after being taken by pirates. Later he wrote Don Quixote, the funny and touching story of a man who reads too many tales of knights and sets off on his own foolish adventures. The book gently makes fun of its dreaming hero while also celebrating his big heart. Don Quixote is often called the first modern novel. Cervantes is honored as the greatest writer in the Spanish language." },

  { slug:'victor_hugo', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'France', birthplace:'Besançon', work:'Les Misérables', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Victor Hugo was a French writer, famous for enormous novels that mix adventure with a deep concern for justice. He was born in the city of Besançon in 1802 and became one of France's most celebrated authors and poets. Hugo cared deeply about the poor and the powerless, and he used his stories to expose the unfairness of society. His novel Les Misérables follows a man named Jean Valjean who is hunted for years after stealing a loaf of bread. Another famous book, The Hunchback of Notre-Dame, helped save the great Paris cathedral from being torn down. Hugo's powerful stories are still read and performed all over the world." },

  { slug:'mark_twain', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'United States', work:'The Adventures of Tom Sawyer', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Mark Twain was an American writer known for his humor and his sharp eye for human nature. He was born Samuel Clemens in a small town in Missouri in 1835 and grew up along the Mississippi River. He took his pen name, Mark Twain, from a riverboat term, and he worked as a printer, a riverboat pilot, and a traveler before becoming a writer. His books The Adventures of Tom Sawyer and Adventures of Huckleberry Finn capture the adventures and troubles of boyhood in America. Twain used comedy to point out greed, dishonesty, and the cruelty of slavery. He is often called the father of American literature." },

  { slug:'fyodor_dostoevsky', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Russia', birthplace:'Moscow', work:'Crime and Punishment', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Fyodor Dostoevsky was a Russian writer famous for novels that dig deep into the human mind. He was born in Moscow in 1821 and led a hard life, once being arrested and nearly executed before his sentence was changed to prison in Siberia. These painful experiences gave him a powerful understanding of guilt, suffering, and hope. His novel Crime and Punishment follows a young man who commits a murder and is slowly crushed by his own conscience. Dostoevsky wrote about big questions of good and evil, faith and doubt. His stories are considered among the greatest and most psychological novels ever written." },

  { slug:'edgar_allan_poe', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Boston', work:'The Raven', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Edgar Allan Poe was an American writer known as a master of mystery and horror. He was born in Boston in 1809 and had a sad, troubled life marked by poverty and loss. Poe wrote spine-tingling short stories full of dread, madness, and the supernatural, such as 'The Tell-Tale Heart.' His famous poem 'The Raven,' with its haunting refrain 'Nevermore,' made him widely known. He is also credited with inventing the modern detective story. Though he struggled during his lifetime, Poe's chilling, imaginative tales have influenced writers and filmmakers ever since." },

  { slug:'mary_shelley', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', birthplace:'London', spouse:'Percy Bysshe Shelley', work:'Frankenstein', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Mary Shelley was an English writer who created one of the most famous stories of all time. She was born in London in 1797 to two well-known writers, and she loved books from an early age. As a teenager on a rainy holiday with friends, she took part in a contest to write a scary story. Her idea became the novel Frankenstein, about a scientist who builds a living creature and then abandons it. The book is often called the first work of science fiction, warning about the dangers of unchecked ambition. She was married to the poet Percy Bysshe Shelley, and her monster has haunted the imagination ever since." },

  { slug:'george_orwell', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', work:'1984', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"George Orwell was an English writer famous for warning about the dangers of dishonest and all-powerful governments. He was born in 1903, and his real name was Eric Blair. Orwell lived through poverty, war, and political struggle, which made him deeply distrustful of those who abuse power. In his novel Animal Farm, farm animals overthrow their farmer only to be ruled by cruel pigs, a clever fable about how revolutions can go wrong. His most famous book, 1984, imagines a future where the government watches and controls everyone's thoughts. Words he invented, like 'Big Brother,' are still used today to describe a loss of freedom." },

  { slug:'dmitri_mendeleev', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Russia', birthplace:'Tobolsk', work:'the periodic table', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Dmitri Mendeleev was a Russian chemist who brought order to the building blocks of matter. He was born in the town of Tobolsk in Siberia in 1834, the youngest of many children. Mendeleev studied the chemical elements — the basic substances that everything is made of — and searched for a pattern among them. In 1869 he arranged the elements into a chart now called the periodic table, grouping them by their properties. Amazingly, he left gaps for elements that had not yet been discovered and correctly predicted what they would be like. His periodic table hangs in science classrooms around the world and remains one of the great achievements of chemistry." },

  { slug:'antoine_lavoisier', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'France', birthplace:'Paris', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Antoine Lavoisier was a French scientist often called the father of modern chemistry. He was born in Paris in 1743 and used careful measurement to turn chemistry into an exact science. Lavoisier proved that matter is never created or destroyed in a chemical reaction, only rearranged — a rule called the conservation of mass. He identified and named important gases, including oxygen, and helped create the system for naming chemicals still used today. Sadly, during the French Revolution he was wrongly executed by guillotine. Yet his precise, careful methods changed chemistry forever." },

  { slug:'kublai_khan', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Mongolia', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Kublai Khan was a Mongol emperor and the grandson of the great conqueror Genghis Khan. He was born in 1215 and completed his family's conquest of China, becoming the first foreign ruler of the whole country. He founded the Yuan dynasty and built a magnificent capital in what is now Beijing. Under his rule, trade flourished along the Silk Road, and he welcomed travelers from far away, including the Italian explorer Marco Polo. Kublai Khan encouraged art, science, and different religions across his vast empire. He is remembered as a powerful ruler who connected the East and West." },

  { slug:'suleiman_the_magnificent', facts:{ field:'sultan', country:'Turkey', birthplace:'Trabzon', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Suleiman the Magnificent was the most powerful sultan of the Ottoman Empire. He was born in the city of Trabzon in 1494 and ruled for 46 years, leading the empire to its golden age. Under Suleiman, Ottoman armies expanded into Europe, the Middle East, and North Africa, making the empire one of the strongest in the world. He was also known as a fair lawmaker, and his people called him 'the Lawgiver.' Suleiman supported great art and architecture, including magnificent mosques still admired today. His long, brilliant reign shaped the history of both Europe and the Middle East." },

  { slug:'akbar', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'India', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Akbar was one of the greatest emperors of the Mughal Empire, which ruled much of India. He was born in 1542 and became emperor as a boy, growing into a wise and powerful leader. Akbar expanded his empire but is especially remembered for how he governed. In a time of religious conflict, he encouraged respect among people of different faiths and even removed a tax on non-Muslims. He welcomed artists, scholars, and thinkers of many religions to his court. Because of his fairness and love of learning, Akbar is honored as one of India's greatest rulers." },

  { slug:'ibn_sina', facts:{ field:'physician', country:'Persia', work:'The Canon of Medicine', era:'over a thousand years ago' },
    text:"Ibn Sina, also known in the West as Avicenna, was a brilliant scholar of the Islamic Golden Age. He was born around 980 in Central Asia and was a child genius who mastered many subjects. Ibn Sina wrote about medicine, science, math, and philosophy, but he is most famous as a doctor. His giant book, The Canon of Medicine, collected and organized medical knowledge so well that it was used in schools for hundreds of years, even in Europe. He helped keep alive and expand the learning of the ancient world. Ibn Sina is remembered as one of the most important thinkers in the history of medicine." },

  { slug:'hammurabi', facts:{ field:'king', country:'Babylon', work:'his code of laws', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Hammurabi was a king of ancient Babylon, in what is now Iraq, who lived in the 1700s BCE. He united many cities under his rule and built one of the first great empires in the region of Mesopotamia. Hammurabi is most famous for creating one of the earliest written sets of laws in history. His code of laws was carved onto a tall stone pillar for everyone to see, so that people would know the rules. Many of the laws followed the idea of 'an eye for an eye,' matching the punishment to the crime. Hammurabi's code shows how ancient people tried to bring order and justice to their societies." },

  { slug:'hannibal', facts:{ field:'general', country:'Carthage', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Hannibal was a general from the ancient city of Carthage, in North Africa, and one of the greatest military commanders in history. He was born around 247 BCE, when Carthage and Rome were bitter enemies fighting for control of the Mediterranean. In a daring move, Hannibal led his army — including war elephants — over the snowy Alps to attack Rome from the north. He won several stunning victories against much larger Roman armies through clever strategy. In the end, Rome recovered and defeated Carthage, but Hannibal's bold tactics are still studied by soldiers today. He remains a legend of courage and military genius." },

  { slug:'pele', facts:{ field:'soccer player', country:'Brazil', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Pelé was a soccer player from Brazil, widely considered one of the greatest athletes of all time. He was born in 1940 and grew up so poor that he practiced with a sock stuffed with rags instead of a real ball. Pelé burst onto the world stage as a teenager, helping Brazil win the World Cup when he was just 17. Fast, skillful, and full of joy, he scored over a thousand goals in his career and won three World Cups. His talent helped make soccer the most popular sport on Earth. Known simply as 'the King,' Pelé became a global symbol of the beautiful game." },

  { slug:'jose_de_san_marti_n', facts:{ field:'general', country:'Argentina', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"José de San Martín was a general who helped free much of South America from Spanish rule. He was born in what is now Argentina in 1778 and trained as a soldier in Europe before returning to fight for his homeland's freedom. In one of history's boldest campaigns, San Martín led an army across the towering Andes Mountains to surprise the Spanish forces. His victories helped win independence for Argentina, Chile, and Peru. Unlike many leaders, he gave up power rather than fight for control after the wars. Together with Simón Bolívar, San Martín is honored as a great liberator of South America." },

  { slug:'alexander_hamilton', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', birthplace:'Nevis', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Alexander Hamilton was one of the Founding Fathers of the United States and its first Secretary of the Treasury. He was born on the Caribbean island of Nevis around 1755, poor and orphaned, but his brilliance won him a chance to study in America. Hamilton fought in the Revolutionary War and became a close aide to General George Washington. After independence, he designed the young country's banking and money system, helping it survive and grow. He also wrote many essays defending the new Constitution. Hamilton's life ended when he was killed in a duel, but his ideas still shape American finance and government." },

  { slug:'thomas_paine', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', birthplace:'Thetford', work:'Common Sense', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Thomas Paine was a writer whose words helped spark the American Revolution. He was born in the town of Thetford, England, in 1737 and moved to America just before the fight for independence began. In early 1776 he published a pamphlet called Common Sense, which argued in plain, powerful language that the colonies should break free from British rule. It sold hundreds of thousands of copies and convinced many ordinary people to support the revolution. Paine believed strongly in liberty and equal rights, and he later took part in the French Revolution too. His fiery writing showed how powerful ideas on paper can change history." },

  { slug:'patrick_henry', facts:{ field:'statesman', country:'United States', era:'in the 1700s' },
    text:"Patrick Henry was an American leader famous for his fiery speeches during the fight for independence. He was born in the colony of Virginia in 1736 and became a skilled lawyer and public speaker. As tensions grew between the colonies and Britain, Henry urged Americans to resist unfair British rule. In one legendary speech, he is said to have cried, 'Give me liberty, or give me death!' — words that stirred the colonists to action. He later served as governor of Virginia and pushed for a Bill of Rights to protect people's freedoms. Patrick Henry is remembered as one of the boldest voices of the American Revolution." },

  { slug:'thurgood_marshall', facts:{ field:'lawyer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Baltimore', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Thurgood Marshall was a lawyer who became the first Black justice of the U.S. Supreme Court. He was born in Baltimore, Maryland, in 1908, at a time when segregation kept Black Americans apart in schools, buses, and stores. As a brilliant lawyer, Marshall fought unfair laws in court, winning case after case. His greatest victory came in 1954, when the Supreme Court agreed that segregated public schools were against the Constitution. In 1967 he was appointed to the Supreme Court himself, where he defended the rights of ordinary people. Thurgood Marshall changed America by proving that the law could be a powerful tool for justice." },

  { slug:'ida_b_wells', facts:{ field:'journalist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Holly Springs', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Ida B. Wells was a brave journalist who fought against racism and violence in the United States. She was born enslaved in Holly Springs, Mississippi, in 1862, just before slavery ended. As a young woman, Wells became a newspaper writer and reported the truth about lynchings — the terrible murders of Black people by mobs. Her fearless reporting made her enemies, and her newspaper office was even destroyed, but she refused to be silenced. She also helped fight for women's right to vote. Ida B. Wells showed that careful, honest journalism could shine a light on injustice and demand change." },

  { slug:'booker_t_washington', facts:{ field:'educator', country:'United States', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Booker T. Washington was an educator who became one of the most influential Black leaders in America. He was born enslaved in Virginia around 1856 and, after freedom came, worked hard to get an education. In 1881 he founded the Tuskegee Institute, a school that trained Black students in useful trades and skills. Washington believed that education and steady economic progress could help Black Americans build better lives. His approach was sometimes criticized by leaders who wanted to demand equal rights more forcefully. Still, Booker T. Washington helped thousands of students and showed the power of education to change lives." },

  { slug:'w_e_b_du_bois', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Great Barrington', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"W. E. B. Du Bois was a writer, scholar, and civil rights leader in the United States. He was born in Great Barrington, Massachusetts, in 1868 and became the first Black person to earn a doctorate from Harvard University. In his book The Souls of Black Folk, Du Bois described the pain and strength of Black life in America. Unlike some leaders of his time, he insisted that Black Americans should demand full equal rights right away. He helped found the NAACP, an organization that still fights for civil rights today. Du Bois spent his long life using his sharp mind and pen to challenge racism." },

  { slug:'malcolm_x', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Omaha', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Malcolm X was a powerful and controversial leader during the American civil rights era. He was born Malcolm Little in Omaha, Nebraska, in 1925 and faced racism, poverty, and hardship growing up. In prison as a young man, he educated himself and became a passionate speaker for Black pride and self-defense. Unlike Martin Luther King Jr., Malcolm X at first argued that Black Americans should not rely on peaceful protest alone. Later in life, after a journey to Mecca, he began to hope for unity among people of all races. Though he was assassinated in 1965, his call for dignity and self-respect still inspires people today." },

  { slug:'cesar_chavez', facts:{ field:'activist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Yuma', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Cesar Chavez was a labor leader who fought for the rights of farmworkers in the United States. He was born near Yuma, Arizona, in 1927, and as a boy his family lost their farm and became migrant workers, picking crops for very low pay. Chavez saw how badly these workers were treated and decided to organize them. He co-founded a union and led peaceful strikes, marches, and boycotts to demand fair wages and safe conditions. His rallying cry, 'Sí, se puede' — 'Yes, it can be done' — gave people hope. Through nonviolent action, Cesar Chavez won real improvements and became a hero to working people." },

  { slug:'george_washington_carver', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'United States', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"George Washington Carver was an American scientist who helped transform farming in the South. He was born enslaved in Missouri around 1864, near the end of the Civil War, and had to fight hard just to get an education. Carver became an expert in plants and soil at the Tuskegee Institute. He taught poor farmers to protect their soil by growing crops like peanuts and sweet potatoes instead of only cotton. Then he invented hundreds of useful products from those crops so farmers could sell them. Carver's clever science and generosity improved the lives of countless struggling farmers." },

  { slug:'sally_ride', facts:{ field:'astronaut', country:'United States', birthplace:'Los Angeles', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Sally Ride was an astronaut who became the first American woman to travel into space. She was born in Los Angeles, California, in 1951 and grew up loving both sports and science, earning a doctorate in physics. In 1983 she flew aboard the space shuttle Challenger, breaking a barrier that had kept American women out of space. Ride helped operate the shuttle's robotic arm and carried out science experiments in orbit. After her flights, she devoted herself to encouraging girls to study science, math, and engineering. Sally Ride proved that space belongs to everyone, no matter their gender." },

  { slug:'duke_ellington', facts:{ field:'composer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Washington', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Duke Ellington was an American composer and bandleader and one of the giants of jazz. He was born in Washington, D.C., in 1899 and earned the nickname 'Duke' for his elegant style. Leading his own orchestra for decades, Ellington wrote and performed thousands of pieces, from toe-tapping dance tunes to grand concert works. He treated jazz as serious art and showcased the special talents of each musician in his band. Songs like 'It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)' became classics. Duke Ellington helped make jazz respected around the world as one of America's greatest gifts to music." },

  { slug:'elizabeth_i', facts:{ field:'queen', country:'England', birthplace:'Greenwich', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Elizabeth I was one of the most famous and successful queens in the history of England. She was born in Greenwich in 1533, the daughter of King Henry VIII. Elizabeth became queen during a dangerous time of religious conflict and threats from foreign powers. She ruled with intelligence and strength, and under her leadership England grew stronger and more united. In 1588 her navy defeated the mighty Spanish Armada, a huge fleet sent to invade. Her long reign, called the Elizabethan era, was a golden age of exploration and of writers like William Shakespeare. Elizabeth never married and is remembered as one of England's greatest rulers." },

  { slug:'louis_xiv', facts:{ field:'king', country:'France', work:'the Palace of Versailles', era:'in the 1500s and 1600s' },
    text:"Louis XIV was the powerful king of France known as the 'Sun King.' He was born in 1638 and became king as a young boy, going on to rule for an astonishing 72 years — the longest of any European monarch. Louis believed a king should have complete power, and he controlled France more tightly than any ruler before him. He built the enormous and glittering Palace of Versailles, where he kept the nobles close and under his eye. Under Louis, France led Europe in art, fashion, and culture, but his many costly wars left the country deep in debt. His grand, absolute rule became a model — and a warning — for kings across Europe." },

  { slug:'augustus', facts:{ field:'emperor', country:'Rome', birthplace:'Rome', era:'in ancient times, before the year 1' },
    text:"Augustus was the first emperor of ancient Rome and the founder of the Roman Empire. He was born in Rome in 63 BCE and was the grand-nephew and heir of Julius Caesar. After Caesar was assassinated, Augustus fought and outmaneuvered his rivals to gain control of Rome. Rather than call himself a king, he cleverly kept the appearance of the old republic while holding real power himself. Under Augustus, Rome enjoyed a long period of peace and prosperity known as the Pax Romana, or 'Roman Peace.' He rebuilt the city in marble and shaped an empire that would last for centuries." },

  { slug:'ernest_hemingway', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'United States', birthplace:'Oak Park', work:'The Old Man and the Sea', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Ernest Hemingway was an American writer famous for his short, powerful sentences and adventurous life. He was born in Oak Park, Illinois, in 1899 and worked as a newspaper reporter before becoming a novelist. Hemingway drove an ambulance in World War I and reported from wars and safaris, using his real experiences in his fiction. He wrote in a plain, direct style that stripped away extra words and influenced countless writers. His short novel The Old Man and the Sea tells of an old fisherman's epic struggle with a giant fish. Hemingway won the Nobel Prize in Literature and remains one of the most admired American authors." },

  { slug:'oscar_wilde', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Ireland', birthplace:'Dublin', work:'The Importance of Being Earnest', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Oscar Wilde was an Irish writer famous for his wit, humor, and sparkling conversation. He was born in Dublin in 1854 and became a celebrity in London for his clever sayings and colorful style. Wilde wrote poems, essays, and one novel, but he is best loved for his comic plays. His play The Importance of Being Earnest pokes fun at the silly manners of high society. He filled his work with clever one-liners that people still quote today. Though his life ended in scandal and hardship, Oscar Wilde is remembered as one of the funniest and most quotable writers in the English language." },

  { slug:'emily_dickinson', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'United States', birthplace:'Amherst', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Emily Dickinson was an American poet whose short, surprising poems are now considered some of the greatest ever written. She was born in Amherst, Massachusetts, in 1830 and lived a quiet, private life, rarely leaving her family's home. Dickinson wrote nearly 1,800 poems, often about nature, death, love, and the mysteries of the soul. Her poems used unusual dashes and slant rhymes that made them feel fresh and modern. Almost none of them were published while she was alive, and her genius was discovered only after she died. Today Emily Dickinson is celebrated as one of America's most original and beloved poets." },

  { slug:'j_r_r_tolkien', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'England', work:'The Lord of the Rings', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"J. R. R. Tolkien was an English writer who created some of the most beloved fantasy stories of all time. He was born in 1892 and became a professor who studied ancient languages and old myths. Tolkien loved language so much that he invented entire imaginary languages, and then built whole worlds to go with them. His books The Hobbit and The Lord of the Rings take place in a richly detailed land called Middle-earth, filled with hobbits, elves, and dragons. These stories about courage, friendship, and the fight against evil have sold hundreds of millions of copies. Tolkien is often called the father of modern fantasy." },

  { slug:'dante_alighieri', facts:{ field:'poet', country:'Italy', birthplace:'Florence', work:'the Divine Comedy', era:'in the Middle Ages' },
    text:"Dante Alighieri was an Italian poet from the Middle Ages, considered one of the greatest writers who ever lived. He was born in the city of Florence around 1265 and became involved in the fierce politics of his time, which got him exiled from his beloved city. In exile, Dante wrote a long poem called the Divine Comedy, which imagines a journey through the afterlife. The poem describes visits to the punishments of the underworld, the mountain of purification, and the glory of paradise. Dante wrote in the everyday Italian language of his region instead of Latin, which helped shape the Italian language itself. His masterpiece has inspired artists and readers for over 700 years." },

  { slug:'salvador_dali', facts:{ field:'painter', country:'Spain', birthplace:'Figueres', work:'Surrealism', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Salvador Dalí was a Spanish painter famous for his strange, dreamlike art. He was born in the town of Figueres in 1904 and showed extraordinary painting skill from a young age. Dalí became a leader of a movement called Surrealism, which tried to paint the wild, illogical images of dreams and the imagination. His most famous painting shows soft, melting clocks draped across a bare landscape. With his curled mustache and outrageous behavior, Dalí turned himself into a walking work of art. His bizarre, unforgettable images made Surrealism one of the most recognizable styles in modern art." },

  { slug:'andy_warhol', facts:{ field:'artist', country:'United States', birthplace:'Pittsburgh', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Andy Warhol was an American artist who became the most famous figure in a movement called Pop Art. He was born in Pittsburgh in 1928 and worked as an advertising illustrator before becoming a fine artist. Warhol turned everyday objects and famous faces into art, creating bright, repeated images of soup cans and movie stars. He believed that art and popular culture — advertising, celebrities, shopping — belonged together. Working in a studio he called 'the Factory,' he also made films and helped launch new music. Warhol changed how people think about art, fame, and the images all around us in modern life." },

  { slug:'niels_bohr', facts:{ field:'scientist', country:'Denmark', birthplace:'Copenhagen', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Niels Bohr was a scientist from Denmark who helped unlock the secrets of the atom. He was born in Copenhagen in 1885 and became one of the leading physicists of his time. Bohr created a new picture of the atom, showing tiny electrons circling a central core, or nucleus. His work was a major step in the strange and powerful science of quantum physics. During World War II, Bohr fled the Nazis and helped other scientists, and afterward he urged the world to use atomic power peacefully. He won the Nobel Prize and trained many young scientists who went on to make discoveries of their own." },

  { slug:'alan_turing', facts:{ field:'mathematician', country:'England', birthplace:'London', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Alan Turing was a mathematician from England whose ideas helped create the modern computer. He was born in London in 1912 and showed a genius for math and logic from an early age. Turing imagined a machine that could follow instructions to solve any problem — a concept at the heart of every computer today. During World War II, he led a secret team that cracked the German military's coded messages, helping the Allies win the war and saving countless lives. After the war, he explored whether machines could one day 'think,' an idea we now call artificial intelligence. Turing was treated cruelly and unfairly for being gay, but today he is honored as a founder of computer science." },

  { slug:'alexander_graham_bell', facts:{ field:'inventor', country:'Scotland', birthplace:'Edinburgh', work:'the telephone', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Alexander Graham Bell was an inventor best known for creating the telephone. He was born in Edinburgh, Scotland, in 1847 and later moved to North America. Bell's mother and wife were both deaf, and he spent much of his life studying sound, speech, and how to help deaf people communicate. This work led him to experiment with sending the human voice through wires. In 1876 he made the first telephone call, speaking to his assistant in another room. The telephone changed the world by letting people talk across great distances, and Bell went on to work on many other inventions throughout his life." },

  { slug:'florence_nightingale', facts:{ field:'nurse', country:'England', era:'in the 1800s' },
    text:"Florence Nightingale was an English nurse who transformed the care of the sick. She was born in 1820 into a wealthy family who expected her to marry, but she felt called to help the suffering. During a war in the 1850s, Nightingale led a team of nurses to care for wounded British soldiers in filthy, crowded hospitals. By insisting on cleanliness, fresh air, and good food, she saved many lives, and soldiers called her 'the Lady with the Lamp' for checking on them at night. Afterward she used careful statistics to prove that clean hospitals saved lives, and she founded a famous nursing school. Florence Nightingale turned nursing into a respected, modern profession." },

  { slug:'ho_chi_minh', facts:{ field:'leader', country:'Vietnam', era:'in the 1900s' },
    text:"Ho Chi Minh was a revolutionary leader who fought for the independence of Vietnam. He was born in 1890, at a time when Vietnam was ruled as a colony by France. As a young man he traveled the world, working many jobs and studying ideas about freedom and communism. Returning home, Ho Chi Minh led a long struggle to free his country, first from France and later during a war involving the United States. He became the leader of North Vietnam and a symbol of his people's fight for independence. Though he died before the war ended, Vietnam's largest city was later renamed Ho Chi Minh City in his honor." },

  { slug:'murasaki_shikibu', facts:{ field:'writer', country:'Japan', work:'The Tale of Genji', era:'over a thousand years ago' },
    text:"Murasaki Shikibu was a writer in ancient Japan who created what many consider the world's first novel. She was born around the year 978 and served as a lady-in-waiting in the royal court during Japan's elegant Heian period. Highly educated at a time when few women were taught to write, she recorded court life in her diary and poems. Her masterpiece, The Tale of Genji, tells the story of a charming prince and the people around him, exploring love, beauty, and sadness. Written a thousand years ago, it is still read and admired today. Murasaki Shikibu is celebrated as one of the greatest writers in Japanese history." },
];
